I'll start by initializing the Go module and creating the first test for our **ReAct Parser**. This parser is the "inner-most" logic that turns LLM text into executable tool calls.

### Phase 1: Skeleton & The First "Red" Test

I will create the directory structure and write a test that defines how we expect the agent to communicate.

#### 1. Initialize Go Module
I'll initialize the module as `github.com/user/armage`.

#### 2. Create `pkg/agent/parser_test.go`
This test will fail because the `Parse` function doesn't exist yet.

```go
package agent

import (
	"testing"
)

func TestParseReAct(t *testing.T) {
	input := `Thought: I should check the files in the current directory.
Action: ls({"path": "."})`

	thought, tool, args, err := Parse(input)
	if err != nil {
		t.Fatalf("Failed to parse: %v", err)
	}

	if thought != "I should check the files in the current directory." {
		t.Errorf("Expected thought to match, got: %s", thought)
	}
	if tool != "ls" {
		t.Errorf("Expected tool 'ls', got: %s", tool)
	}
	if args != `{"path": "."}` {
		t.Errorf("Expected args '{\"path\": \".\"}', got: %s", args)
	}
}
```

